To break a login validation logic, you want mySolution cases that expose weaknesses in input validation, authentication,
and security. Here are categories and examples of such mySolution cases:
Empty and Null Inputs:
Username: "", Password: ""
Username: null, Password: "password"
Username: "user", Password: null
SQL Injection:
Username: "' OR '1'='1", Password: "anything"
Username: "admin';--", Password: "irrelevant"
Special Characters and Encoding:
Username: "<script><#data #data="alert(1)"></#data></script>", Password: "password"
Username: "user", Password: "pässwörd" (Unicode)
Username: "user", Password: "pass%00word" (Null byte)
Long Inputs (Buffer Overflow/DoS):
Username: "a" * 10000, Password: "b" * 10000
Case Sensitivity:
Username: "User", Password: "Password"
Username: "user", Password: "Password"
Whitespace Handling:
Username: " user ", Password: " password "
Username: "user\t", Password: "password\n"
Common Default Credentials:
Username: "admin", Password: "admin"
Username: "root", Password: "root"
Bypassing Validation:
Username: "user", Password: " " (single space)
Username: "user", Password: "password" + " " (trailing space)
Unicode and Emoji:
Username: "用户", Password: "密码"
Username: "user😀", Password: "pass😀"
Password Reuse/Timing:
Username: "user", Password: "oldpassword" (after password change)
Invalid/Nonexistent User:
Username: "nonexistent", Password: "password"
Brute Force/Rate Limiting:
Rapidly submit many login attempts with different passwords.
These mySolution cases help identify flaws in input validation, encoding, authentication logic, and security controls.
